nd"},"en":{"1272–1292":"1272–1292","1269–1292":"1269–1292","1288–1359":"1288–1359","1250–Male":"1250–Deceased","1250–Female":"1250–Deceased","1359":"1359","1269":"1269","1288":"1288","1274":"1274","about 1288":"about 1288","1272":"1272","before 1272":"before 1272","1250":"1250","1292":"1292","Europe":"Europe","Withiel, Cornwall, England":"Withiel, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","Helston, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"Helston, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","Trenoweth, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Trenaco","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Spanish: probably a nickname from <i>trenado</i> ‘arranged in a shape of hair-net, lattice or plait’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Johanna","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["feminine form of <i>Johannes</i> (  see  John  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Johannah","meanings":["feminine form of <i>Johannes</i> (  see  John  )."]},{"name":"Jonna","meanings":["contracted form of   Johanna ."]},{"name":"Jane","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Johanna Trenaco was born in 1272, in Withiel, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom, her father, Richard De Trenance, was 23 and her mother, Mrs Richard de Trenance, was 23. She had at least 1 son with Stephen Trenoweth. She died in 1292, in her hometown, at the age of 20."},"et":{"1272–1292":"1272–1292","1269–1292":"1269–1292","1288–1359":"1288–1359","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1250–Female":"1250–Surnud","1359":"1359","1269":"1269","1288":"1288","1274":"1274","about 1288":"umbes 1288","1272":"1272","before 1272":"enne 1272","1250":"1250","1292":"1292","Europe":"Europe","Withiel, Cornwall, England":"Withiel, Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Helston, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"Helston, Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Trenoweth, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England"},"fi":{"1272–1292":"1272–1292","1269–1292":"1269–1292","1288–1359":"1288–1359","1250–Male":"1250–Kuollut","1250–Female":"1250–Kuollut","1359":"1359","1269":"1269","1288":"1288","1274":"1274","about 1288":"noin 1288","1272":"1272","before 1272":"ennen vuotta 1272","1250":"1250","1292":"1292","Europe":"Europe","Withiel, Cornwall, England":"Withiel, Cornwall, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Helston, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"Helston, Cornwall, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Trenoweth, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, En